.TH "WORKERGLOBALSCOPE.SETTIMEOUT" "3JS" "December 30, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
WorkerGlobalScope.setTimeout \- WorkerGlobalScope: setTimeout() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This feature is only available in Web Workers.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] When the \f[CR]code\f[R] parameter is used, this
method dynamically executes its value as JavaScript.
APIs like this are known as injection sinks, and are potentially a
vector for cross\-site\-scripting (XSS) attacks.
.PP
You can mitigate this risk by always assigning \f[CR]TrustedScript\f[R]
objects instead of strings and enforcing trusted types.
See Security considerations in \f[CR]Window.setTimeout()\f[R] for more
information.
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]setTimeout()\f[B]\f[R] method of the
\f[CR]WorkerGlobalScope\f[R] interface sets a timer which executes a
function or specified piece of code once the timer expires.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
setTimeout(code)
setTimeout(code, delay)

setTimeout(func)
setTimeout(func, delay)
setTimeout(func, delay, param1)
setTimeout(func, delay, param1, param2)
setTimeout(func, delay, param1, param2, /* \&..., */ paramN)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]func\f[R]
A \f[CR]function\f[R] to be executed after the timer expires.
.TP
\f[B]code\f[R]
A \f[CR]TrustedScript\f[R] or a string of arbitrary code that is
compiled and executed every \f[CR]delay\f[R] milliseconds.
This can be used instead of passing a function, but is \f[I]strongly
discouraged\f[R] for the same reasons that make using \f[CR]eval()\f[R]
a security risk.
.TP
\f[B]delay\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
The time that the timer should wait before the specified function or
code is executed, in milliseconds.
Defaults to 0 if not specified.
.RS
.PP
Note:
.IP \(bu 2
The delay has a maximum value of 2147483647 ms \(em specifying larger
values may result in overflow or a 0 value being used.
See maximum delay value for more information.
.IP \(bu 2
The actual delay may be longer than set.
For example, setting \f[CR]delay\f[R] to 0 will execute in the next
event cycle rather than \(lqimmediately\(rq.
See Reasons for longer delays than specified for more information.
.IP \(bu 2
If the value isn\(cqt a number, implicit type coercion is silently done
on the value to convert it to a number.
This can lead to unexpected and surprising results \(em see Non\-number
delay values are silently coerced into numbers for an example.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]param1\f[R], \&..., \f[B]paramN\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
Additional arguments which are passed through to the function specified
by \f[CR]func\f[R].
.SS Return value
A positive integer (typically within the range of 1 to 2,147,483,647)
that uniquely identifies the timer created by the call.
This identifier, often referred to as a \(lqtimeout ID\(rq, can be
passed to \f[CR]clearTimeout()\f[R] to cancel the timer.
.PP
Within the same global environment (e.g., a specific window or worker)
the timeout ID is guaranteed not to be reused for any new timer as long
as the original timer remains active.
However, separate global environments maintain their own independent
pools of timer IDs.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]SyntaxError\f[R]
The \f[CR]code\f[R] can\(cqt be parsed as a script.
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if the \f[CR]code\f[R] parameter is set to a string when Trusted
Types are enforced by a CSP and no default policy is defined.
It is also thrown if the first parameter is not one of the supported
types: a function, string or \f[CR]TrustedScript\f[R].
.SH DESCRIPTION
See \f[CR]Window.setTimeout()\f[R] for detailed descriptions.
.SH EXAMPLES
See \f[CR]Window.setTimeout()\f[R] for examples.
